Your damage nuke only = 62185<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> PitounetEQ:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->Possible explanatons : <br>
- Mages need a severe nerf. Wizards SHOULD be the uncontested master of DD (halfing their nuke efficiency seems about right due to your parse) <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->That mages may or may not need a nerf is not an explanation.  This is an important point, because you need to explain the damage numbers before you can decide whether an adjustment is necessary.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, class balance is not the only way to look at things.  Way too many people do this...  I've fallen victim myself numerous times... but they take the idea that classes need to be perfectly balanced an think that it's holy or something.  Someday people are going to have to face the fact that classes will <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>never</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be perfectly balanced.  The game is way too old and the game is way too big for it to ever be perfectly achieved.  Yes, class balance is important, I'm not saying it isn't, but one also needs to look at a class from its own perspective only.<br>
<br>
I know this seems funny, since usually I am interested in all classes at once and expect others to do the same, but when I say look at a class from its own perspective I really mean look at every class that way.  And what I mean by this is to see if each class is fun to play.  Of course one factor of being fun to play is feeling useful in groups, which is where balance comes in.  But you need to be careful not to take balancing so far that the different classes are no longer fun.. or worse, no longer different.<br>
<br>
Mages to a lot of things other than nuking, honestly I've been doing a lot of healing/boot-nuking lately, and many mages chain pets.  But the thing is, if you take nukes away from a magician or nerf them too badly, someone playing a magician will <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>often</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> find himself in a situation where he has nothing useful to do, and there is nothing he can do about it.  This is the exact issue clerics had.  Sure, he can contribute in valuable ways by using his pet, damage shield, and malo spells, but other than that he'd be standing around doing nothing most of the time, which might be a bigger problem than if the pet's contribution was half what everyone thought it should be.<br>
<br>
Anyway that's my rant for the night..  Again, it's not necessarily MORE important than interclass balance, but it is still very important and it is forgotten much more often.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> - Your wizards were making the washing up while playing because they knew your group was rocking and their damage was not really needed (When you parse you must make sure that everyone plays at his best). <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Maybe...  but then not everyone always plays their best.  If every parse was from players playing their absolute best then we'd have a much more innaccurate view of how the game works, particularly in experience groups, where there has been noted a tendency to exaggerate your accomplishments and misinterpret your memories of what actually happened, particularly in regards to group uptime rates.<br>
